The paper deals with compressed sensing, which is a topic in information theory (cs.IT). The focus is on one-bit compressed sensing, which is a subfield of compressed sensing that deals with quantized measurements (cs.SP). The paper also discusses the use of non-Gaussian measurement matrices, which is a topic in machine learning (cs.LG) and signal processing (cs.SP). The paper's use of a new random hyperplane tessellation result suggests that it may also be relevant to numerical analysis (cs.NA) and multimedia (cs.MM).
